The start symbol S can only expand in one of three ways:

1. S → NT101 NT109  
   NT101 directly produces the terminal t11, so any sentence derived from this rule starts with t11.

2. S → NT93 NT16  
   The only way for NT93 to begin with t0 is through NT93 → NT98 NT9, because NT98 → t0.  
   That expansion necessarily yields the first two terminals “t0 t6”.  
   Our string’s first two terminals are “t0 t7”, so this rule cannot match the string.

3. S → NT10 NT87  
   All possibilities for NT10 begin with one of the terminals t7, t14, t6, t11, t9 or t4 (by tracing every production headed by NT10).  
   None of these options starts with t0.

Hence, no derivation from the start symbol can produce a sentence whose very first terminal is t0 followed by t7.  
Because the given string begins “t0 t7 …”, it cannot be generated by the grammar.
